The '''Dr. Hadwen Trust''' ('''DHT''') is the UK's leading medical research charity that funds and promotes exclusively non-animal techniques to [[Alternatives to animal testing|replace animal experiments]].<ref name="MNT">[http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/118286.php Pain Experts Say Greater Focus On High-Tech Non-Animal Research Could Help Thousands Of Patients] 15 August 2008 [[Medical News Today]]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/7561061.stm Call to end animal pain-research] 14 August 2008 [[BBC News]]</ref><ref>[http://www.politics.co.uk/opinion-formers/press-releases/animal-welfare/dr-hadwen-trust-eu-parliament-vote-on-animal-experiments-law-gives-“a-glimmer-of-hope-for-animals-but-doesn-t-go-far-enough--$1293212$447630.htm Dr Hadwen Trust: EU Parliament vote on animal experiments law gives “a glimmer of hope for animals but doesn't go far enough."] 05, May 2009 politics.co.uk</ref> Established in 1970 (Registered charity number 261096), the work undertaken by the Dr Hadwen Trust benefits humans with the development of more relevant and reliable science whilst also benefiting laboratory animals.

The portfolio of work funded by the Dr. Hadwen Trust is high-quality, peer-reviewed and innovative research, combining strict ethical principles and scientific excellence.  Projects receiving funding from the Dr. Hadwen Trust range from [[epilepsy]], [[multiple sclerosis]],<ref>[http://www.msrc.co.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=show&pageid=2213&CFID=1100409&CFTOKEN=66847616 Multiple Sclerosis Resource Centre RNA and RNAi] The Multiple Sclerosis Resource Centre</ref> [[Breast cancer|breast]]<ref>[http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/144138.php Breast Cancer In A Test Tube Wins Prize For Replacing Laboratory Animals] 30 March 2009 [[Medical News Today]]</ref> and [[skin cancer]], [[meningitis]], [[asthma]], [[diabetes]] and [[drug testing]], to [[arthritis]], [[Parkinson's disease|Parkinson]]’s disease, [[lung]] injury, [[whooping cough]], [[Vaccine|vaccine testing]], [[dentistry]], [[heart disease]], [[tropical medicine|tropical illness]], [[fetal development]], [[Brain tumor|brain tumours]] and [[AIDS]].

The Dr Hadwen Trust is internationally recognised as a leading authority on replacing animal experiments and actively promotes the concept and practice of non-animal research through its policy work, publications, science community outreach and the media. Active membership of the International Council for Animal Protection in OECD Programmes (ICAPO) enable the Dr Hadwen Trust to transmit its message globally and effectively. 

